# Rust Code Patterns for u-forge.ai

## Error Handling

Use `anyhow::Result` for application-level errors throughout the codebase.

For typed error enums at system boundaries (e.g. HTTP handler responses), use
`#[derive(thiserror::Error)]` instead of hand-writing `Display` and `From` impls.
`thiserror = "2.0"` is already in `Cargo.toml`.

```rust
#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]
pub enum AppError {
    #[error("Not found: {0}")]
    NotFound(String),
    #[error("Internal error: {0}")]
    Internal(#[from] anyhow::Error),  // generates From<anyhow::Error> + std::error::Error
}
```

For internal fallible operations, keep using `anyhow`:

```rust
use anyhow::{anyhow, Context, Result};

pub async fn embed(&self, text: &str) -> Result<Vec<f32>> {
    let resp = self.client
        .post(format!("{}/embeddings", self.base_url))
        .header("Authorization", "Bearer lemonade")
        .json(&body)
        .send().await
        .map_err(|e| anyhow!("Lemonade request failed: {}", e))?
        .json::<serde_json::Value>().await
        .context("Failed to parse Lemonade response")?;
    // ...
}
```

Use `.context()` for wrapping lower-level errors (e.g. SQLite, I/O).
Use `anyhow!(...)` for constructing new errors with formatting.

